Operation of fields: 
 
Fields will begin dosing when PLC1 - B009, off time between cycles, has expired. The 
fields will dose sequentially one after the other, without stopping, until all fields have 
dosed. Each field can have different dose times as set in PLC1 - B001 thru B006. At the 
end of a complete cycle of dosing all 6 fields, the off time, PLC1 - B009, will begin. After 
a set number of cycles of field dosing, as set in PLC1 - B010, each field will flush for a 
time as set in PLC1 - B011 thru B016. Each field can have a different flushing time. 
Field flushing is a separate event not tied to dosing and will occur at the end of an off 
time sequentially similar to the dosing sequence. Typically the field flushing time will be 
shorter than the dosing time for the field. 
 
Upon power restoration, normal water level restoration, or low water level stop, if a field 
was dosing, the system will continue but will start with the next field in the sequence. If 
the power failure was during an off period, the off time will continue where it left off. 
Upon power restoration, there is a 2 minute delay before the pumps are allowed to start.

CP-4097  04/12/12 
 
Operation of filters: 
 
When the differential pressure switch closes for PLC2 - B003  seconds, indicating that it 
is time to flush the filters, filter 1 will flush for PLC 2 - B001 (ON) seconds. Filter 2 will 
then flush for B001 (ON) seconds. This will repeat for 4 filters. Once filters begin 
flushing they will continue to flush until all selected filters are flushed. 
 
 
During a cycle of flushing, the differential pressure switch should open indicating that 
the filters are clean.  
 
 
If the switch does not open, then another cycle of flushing will occur if PLC2 - B002 is 
set to 2 or more. The maximum number of filter flush cycles for a given complete field 
dosing cycle is limited to B002 times. If after B002 flush cycles, the differential pressure 
switch still has not opened, then the filter flushing will stop and the PLC will output to an 
alarm. When the field dosing is complete, no water will be flowing through the filters, so 
the differential pressure switch will open and this in turn will reset the filter flush cycles 
to 0 which will allow the same procedure to repeat on the next field dosing cycle. 
 
In addition to differential pressure initiating flushing, a filter flush will occur at the end of 
field dosing cycle PLC1 – B019. If a filter is to be taken out of service, turn its HOA 
switch to OFF position. The filter flush sequence will then skip flushing this filter.  
 
Operation of pumps: 
 
Pumps are controlled by a duplex alternator which will alternate the pumps in a 
standard duplex manner. Only 1 pump will be allowed to run during field dosing, filter 
flushing and field flushing. Either pump can be taken out of service without affecting the 
operation. 
 
Operation of Drain Valve: 
 
When the pumps turn off, the pump drain valve, field supply drain valve and field drain 
valve open, and remain open until a pump starts. 
 
Motor Control: 
 
Motor starters (VFD’s) are external to this control panel and are furnished by others. 
This panel will provide dry contacts for start/stop and will need dry contacts from the 
motor starters (VFD’s) indicating that the motor is running.
